162. Find Peak Element
Problem

A peak element is an element that is strictly greater than its neighbors.

Given an integer array nums, return the index of any peak element.

You may assume:

nums[-1] = -∞
nums[n] = -∞

You must write an algorithm with O(log n) time complexity.

Example 1
Input: nums = [1,2,3,1]

Output: 2

Explanation

3 > 2 and 3 > 1
Example 2
Input: nums = [1,2,1,3,5,6,4]

Output: 1 or 5

Both indices are valid because both are peak elements.

Approach 1: Brute Force (Check Every Element)
Intuition

Traverse every element and check whether it is greater than its left and right neighbors.

Handle the first and last elements separately.

Java
class Solution {
    public int findPeakElement(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;

        if (n == 1)
            return 0;

        if (nums[0] > nums[1])
            return 0;

        if (nums[n - 1] > nums[n - 2])
            return n - 1;

        for (int i = 1; i < n - 1; i++) {

            if (nums[i] > nums[i - 1] &&
                nums[i] > nums[i + 1]) {

                return i;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
}
Dry Run
nums = [1,2,3,1]
i = 0

1 > 2 ❌
i = 1

2 > 1 ✔

2 > 3 ❌
i = 2

3 > 2 ✔

3 > 1 ✔

Return

2
Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)

Approach 2: Better (Find Maximum Element)
Intuition

The maximum element is always a peak because it is greater than all other elements.

Simply find the maximum element and return its index.

Note: This works because the global maximum is always a valid peak, but it does not satisfy the required O(log n) complexity.

Java
class Solution {
    public int findPeakElement(int[] nums) {

        int maxIndex = 0;

        for (int i = 1; i < nums.length; i++) {

            if (nums[i] > nums[maxIndex]) {
                maxIndex = i;
            }
        }

        return maxIndex;
    }
}
Dry Run
nums = [1,2,3,1]
Maximum = 3

Index = 2

Return

2
Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)

Approach 3: Binary Search (Optimal)
Intuition

Instead of finding the peak directly, compare:

nums[mid]

with

nums[mid + 1]
Case 1
nums[mid] < nums[mid+1]

The array is increasing.

A peak must exist on the right side.

Move right.

low = mid + 1
Case 2
nums[mid] > nums[mid+1]

The array is decreasing.

A peak exists on the left side (possibly mid itself).

Move left.

high = mid

Eventually,

low == high

which is the peak index.

Java
class Solution {
    public int findPeakElement(int[] nums) {

        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;

        while (low < high) {

            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] < nums[mid + 1]) {
                low = mid + 1;
            } else {
                high = mid;
            }
        }

        return low;
    }
}
